1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,037
Two men in police uniforms walked

2
00:00:02,104 --> 00:00:04,017
into a Boston museum and walked

3
00:00:04,084 --> 00:00:05,998
out with half a billion dollars

4
00:00:06,064 --> 00:00:08,286
of masterpieces. Eighty-one minutes.

5
00:00:08,353 --> 00:00:10,575
Thirteen works. And more than thirty

6
00:00:10,642 --> 00:00:12,185
years later — not one has

7
00:00:12,252 --> 00:00:13,252
ever been found.

8
00:00:15,528 --> 00:00:17,874
Walk into the Isabella Stewart Gardner

9
00:00:17,940 --> 00:00:19,854
Museum in Boston today, and you

10
00:00:19,921 --> 00:00:22,081
will find something that should not

11
00:00:22,148 --> 00:00:24,061
be there. Or rather — something

12
00:00:24,128 --> 00:00:25,128
that isn't.

13
00:00:27,248 --> 00:00:29,408
On the walls, between the paintings

14
00:00:29,475 --> 00:00:31,389
that remain, hang empty frames.

15
00:00:31,455 --> 00:00:33,801
Gilded, ornate, and holding nothing at

16
00:00:33,868 --> 00:00:35,596
all. They are not a mistake,

17
00:00:35,663 --> 00:00:36,959
and they are not art.

18
00:00:37,026 --> 00:00:38,939
They are the exact spaces where

19
00:00:39,006 --> 00:00:41,167
some of the most valuable paintings

20
00:00:41,233 --> 00:00:42,529
on earth used to be —

21
00:00:42,596 --> 00:00:44,942
left hanging, deliberately, as a wound

22
00:00:45,008 --> 00:00:46,922
the museum refuses to cover up.

23
00:00:50,811 --> 00:00:52,539
Because on a single night in

24
00:00:52,606 --> 00:00:54,581
1990, those frames were emptied.

25
00:00:54,648 --> 00:00:56,623
Two men talked their way through

26
00:00:56,690 --> 00:00:58,480
the door, tied up the guards,

27
00:00:58,547 --> 00:01:00,213
and spent the next hour and

28
00:01:00,280 --> 00:01:02,688
twenty minutes taking thirteen works of

29
00:01:02,754 --> 00:01:04,606
art worth, by common estimate,

30
00:01:04,673 --> 00:01:06,525
around half a billion dollars.

31
00:01:07,733 --> 00:01:09,338
The FBI would come to call

32
00:01:09,405 --> 00:01:11,380
it the largest property crime in

33
00:01:11,447 --> 00:01:13,484
the history of the United States.

34
00:01:13,550 --> 00:01:15,464
The museum calls it the largest

35
00:01:15,531 --> 00:01:16,827
art heist in history.

36
00:01:16,893 --> 00:01:18,437
And whatever you call it,

37
00:01:18,503 --> 00:01:20,293
it shares one more title that

38
00:01:20,360 --> 00:01:22,459
has never changed: it is unsolved.

39
00:01:23,168 --> 00:01:24,896
No one has ever been charged

40
00:01:24,963 --> 00:01:25,963
with the theft.

41
00:01:26,030 --> 00:01:27,449
Not a single one of the

42
00:01:27,516 --> 00:01:29,924
thirteen works has ever been recovered.

43
00:01:29,990 --> 00:01:32,212
The thieves have never been publicly

44
00:01:32,279 --> 00:01:34,316
named. And the empty frames still

45
00:01:34,383 --> 00:01:35,383
hang, waiting.

46
00:01:36,142 --> 00:01:37,809
We are drawn to crimes that

47
00:01:37,875 --> 00:01:39,789
end. The confession, the trial,

48
00:01:39,856 --> 00:01:42,016
the verdict, the cell door closing.

49
00:01:42,083 --> 00:01:43,564
This is not one of those

50
00:01:43,631 --> 00:01:45,359
crimes. This is the one that

51
00:01:45,426 --> 00:01:47,278
got away so completely that it

52
00:01:47,344 --> 00:01:49,073
has slipped out of the world

53
00:01:49,140 --> 00:01:51,177
of police work and into something

54
00:01:51,243 --> 00:01:53,157
like folklore — except the loss

55
00:01:53,223 --> 00:01:54,952
is utterly real, and you can

56
00:01:55,019 --> 00:01:56,315
stand in front of it.

57
00:01:56,382 --> 00:01:58,233
That is what makes the Gardner

58
00:01:58,300 --> 00:02:00,461
heist different. There is no ending

59
00:02:00,527 --> 00:02:02,132
to spoil. Only an absence,

60
00:02:02,199 --> 00:02:03,989
framed in gold, that has been

61
00:02:04,056 --> 00:02:05,969
waiting longer than many of the

62
00:02:06,036 --> 00:02:08,320
people watching this have been alive.

63
00:02:12,290 --> 00:02:13,771
This is the story of how

64
00:02:13,838 --> 00:02:15,752
it happened — minute by minute.

65
00:02:15,818 --> 00:02:17,855
What exactly vanished, and why it

66
00:02:17,922 --> 00:02:19,465
can never simply be sold.

67
00:02:19,532 --> 00:02:21,569
Everything the FBI will and won't

68
00:02:21,636 --> 00:02:22,932
say about who did it.

69
00:02:22,999 --> 00:02:24,850
And why, after more than three

70
00:02:24,917 --> 00:02:27,386
decades and a ten-million-dollar reward,

71
00:02:27,453 --> 00:02:29,181
the most famous art theft in

72
00:02:29,248 --> 00:02:30,976
the world is still a mystery

73
00:02:31,043 --> 00:02:33,018
with empty frames for an answer.

74
00:02:33,670 --> 00:02:35,460
It begins, as the best heists

75
00:02:35,527 --> 00:02:37,132
do, with a quiet night and

76
00:02:37,198 --> 00:02:38,198
a small lie.

77
00:02:40,653 --> 00:02:42,258
It is the early morning of

78
00:02:42,325 --> 00:02:43,374
March 18th, 1990.

79
00:02:43,441 --> 00:02:45,416
Boston is still coming down from

80
00:02:45,483 --> 00:02:46,594
St. Patrick's Day.

81
00:02:46,660 --> 00:02:48,574
The streets near the museum are

82
00:02:48,641 --> 00:02:51,110
empty. Inside, two young security guards

83
00:02:51,176 --> 00:02:53,213
are doing the most ordinary thing

84
00:02:53,280 --> 00:02:54,823
in the world — watching a

85
00:02:54,890 --> 00:02:57,112
building where nothing ever happens.

86
00:02:57,668 --> 00:02:59,273
At around half past one in

87
00:02:59,340 --> 00:03:01,253
the morning, a buzzer sounds at

88
00:03:01,320 --> 00:03:02,320
a side entrance.

89
00:03:02,387 --> 00:03:04,300
Outside stand two men in police

90
00:03:04,367 --> 00:03:06,712
uniforms. They say they are responding

91
00:03:06,779 --> 00:03:08,631
to a disturbance, a call about

92
00:03:08,698 --> 00:03:10,673
the grounds. They look the part.

93
00:03:10,740 --> 00:03:11,974
They sound the part.

94
00:03:12,732 --> 00:03:14,399
And here is the first hinge

95
00:03:14,465 --> 00:03:15,823
of the whole story — a

96
00:03:15,890 --> 00:03:17,248
single human decision.

97
00:03:17,315 --> 00:03:19,167
One of the guards, against the

98
00:03:19,233 --> 00:03:21,394
museum's own rules, buzzes them in.

99
00:03:21,460 --> 00:03:22,942
It is the kind of small,

100
00:03:23,009 --> 00:03:25,478
understandable mistake anyone might make

101
00:03:25,544 --> 00:03:27,581
at one-thirty in the morning when

102
00:03:27,648 --> 00:03:29,747
authority is standing at the door.

103
00:03:29,813 --> 00:03:31,295
He had no way of knowing

104
00:03:31,362 --> 00:03:33,460
it would become the most expensive

105
00:03:33,527 --> 00:03:34,576
door ever opened.

106
00:03:35,923 --> 00:03:37,528
It is worth pausing on why

107
00:03:37,595 --> 00:03:39,446
that worked, because it is the

108
00:03:39,513 --> 00:03:41,488
quiet engine of the whole crime.

109
00:03:41,555 --> 00:03:42,913
A uniform is a kind of

110
00:03:42,980 --> 00:03:44,955
key that opens doors no lockpick

111
00:03:45,022 --> 00:03:46,688
can. We are trained, all of

112
00:03:46,755 --> 00:03:48,360
us, to relax a little when

113
00:03:48,427 --> 00:03:50,525
authority arrives — to assume that

114
00:03:50,592 --> 00:03:52,321
the person in the uniform is

115
00:03:52,387 --> 00:03:54,177
the solution, not the threat.

116
00:03:54,244 --> 00:03:56,034
The thieves did not break in.

117
00:03:56,101 --> 00:03:57,706
They were invited in, by a

118
00:03:57,772 --> 00:03:59,995
frightened young man doing what most

119
00:04:00,061 --> 00:04:01,481
of us would do when the

120
00:04:01,548 --> 00:04:03,338
police say there's a problem.

121
00:04:03,404 --> 00:04:05,688
The first and biggest security system

122
00:04:05,755 --> 00:04:07,669
the museum had was human trust.

123
00:04:07,735 --> 00:04:09,340
And it was defeated with a

124
00:04:09,407 --> 00:04:10,407
costume.

125
00:04:12,860 --> 00:04:14,959
Once inside, the men move quickly.

126
00:04:15,025 --> 00:04:16,754
They tell the guard there is

127
00:04:16,820 --> 00:04:18,425
a warrant for his arrest —

128
00:04:18,492 --> 00:04:19,974
and ask him to step away

129
00:04:20,040 --> 00:04:21,830
from the only alarm button in

130
00:04:21,897 --> 00:04:23,255
the building. He does.

131
00:04:23,322 --> 00:04:25,235
They call the second guard down

132
00:04:25,302 --> 00:04:27,277
too. And in moments, the costume

133
00:04:27,344 --> 00:04:29,319
drops, and the truth is obvious:

134
00:04:29,386 --> 00:04:30,682
these are not police.

135
00:04:32,522 --> 00:04:34,868
The guards are handcuffed, walked down

136
00:04:34,934 --> 00:04:36,663
to the basement, and bound —

137
00:04:36,729 --> 00:04:39,199
their wrists cuffed, their heads wrapped

138
00:04:39,265 --> 00:04:40,265
in duct tape.

139
00:04:40,332 --> 00:04:41,875
And there they will stay,

140
00:04:41,942 --> 00:04:43,979
helpless in the dark, while above

141
00:04:44,045 --> 00:04:46,021
them the most valuable art theft

142
00:04:46,087 --> 00:04:48,063
in history unfolds in real time.

143
00:04:48,129 --> 00:04:50,475
Remember that: the guards were victims

144
00:04:50,542 --> 00:04:52,085
too. They were tied up in

145
00:04:52,152 --> 00:04:53,695
a basement, not let in on

146
00:04:53,762 --> 00:04:54,762
a secret.

147
00:04:55,016 --> 00:04:56,744
Now the thieves have the run

148
00:04:56,811 --> 00:04:57,811
of the museum.

149
00:04:57,878 --> 00:04:59,915
And the building is watching them

150
00:04:59,981 --> 00:05:02,204
— silently. Motion detectors quietly

151
00:05:02,270 --> 00:05:04,431
record their movements as they move

152
00:05:04,497 --> 00:05:05,979
from gallery to gallery.

153
00:05:06,046 --> 00:05:08,021
There is, somewhere, a record of

154
00:05:08,088 --> 00:05:09,754
their footsteps that night.

155
00:05:09,821 --> 00:05:11,241
What there is not, is a

156
00:05:11,307 --> 00:05:12,307
single face.

157
00:05:13,377 --> 00:05:14,735
Picture the next hour.

158
00:05:14,802 --> 00:05:16,283
A great museum at two in

159
00:05:16,350 --> 00:05:18,140
the morning, dark and hushed,

160
00:05:18,207 --> 00:05:20,491
hung with centuries of masterpieces —

161
00:05:20,557 --> 00:05:22,347
and two men moving through it

162
00:05:22,414 --> 00:05:24,142
alone, in no apparent hurry,

163
00:05:24,209 --> 00:05:25,691
with all the time in the

164
00:05:25,757 --> 00:05:27,424
world. No alarm rang out to

165
00:05:27,491 --> 00:05:29,651
the police. The only witnesses were

166
00:05:29,718 --> 00:05:31,817
the silent sensors in the ceilings

167
00:05:31,883 --> 00:05:33,550
and the two guards bound in

168
00:05:33,617 --> 00:05:36,209
the basement below, listening to footsteps

169
00:05:36,276 --> 00:05:37,942
overhead and unable to do a

170
00:05:38,009 --> 00:05:39,367
single thing about it.

171
00:05:39,434 --> 00:05:40,915
It is one of the eeriest

172
00:05:40,982 --> 00:05:42,896
scenes in the history of crime:

173
00:05:42,962 --> 00:05:45,555
an unhurried robbery of the irreplaceable,

174
00:05:45,621 --> 00:05:47,041
with no one to stop it.

175
00:05:49,293 --> 00:05:50,898
They go first to the Dutch

176
00:05:50,965 --> 00:05:52,570
Room, on the second floor,

177
00:05:52,636 --> 00:05:53,994
where the giants hang.

178
00:05:54,061 --> 00:05:55,974
And here they do something that

179
00:05:56,041 --> 00:05:58,078
still makes art historians wince.

180
00:05:58,145 --> 00:06:00,676
Rather than carefully lift the paintings,

181
00:06:00,742 --> 00:06:03,212
they cut two enormous Rembrandt canvases

182
00:06:03,278 --> 00:06:04,513
out of their frames.

183
00:06:04,579 --> 00:06:06,555
You can almost feel the violence

184
00:06:06,621 --> 00:06:08,041
of it — a blade against

185
00:06:08,108 --> 00:06:10,515
three-hundred-and-fifty-year-old paint.

186
00:06:10,812 --> 00:06:12,479
They work for over an hour.

187
00:06:12,545 --> 00:06:14,768
Methodical in some ways, baffling in

188
00:06:14,834 --> 00:06:17,242
others. They take some masterpieces and

189
00:06:17,308 --> 00:06:19,469
walk straight past others that were

190
00:06:19,535 --> 00:06:20,535
worth even more.

191
00:06:20,602 --> 00:06:22,824
They ignore the single most valuable

192
00:06:22,891 --> 00:06:24,805
painting in the building by one

193
00:06:24,871 --> 00:06:27,093
measure, and grab an ordinary bronze

194
00:06:27,160 --> 00:06:28,456
eagle off a flagpole.

195
00:06:28,523 --> 00:06:30,313
Whatever this was, it was not

196
00:06:30,380 --> 00:06:32,293
the work of refined art thieves

197
00:06:32,360 --> 00:06:33,656
with a shopping list.

198
00:06:33,723 --> 00:06:35,205
At a quarter to three in

199
00:06:35,271 --> 00:06:37,247
the morning, they leave — making

200
00:06:37,313 --> 00:06:38,980
two separate trips out to a

201
00:06:39,047 --> 00:06:40,047
car, arms full.

202
00:06:40,113 --> 00:06:41,113
The doors close.

203
00:06:41,180 --> 00:06:43,093
The museum sits silent over its

204
00:06:43,160 --> 00:06:44,210
two bound guards.

205
00:06:44,276 --> 00:06:46,128
And by the time anyone arrives

206
00:06:46,195 --> 00:06:48,047
the next morning to find them,

207
00:06:48,113 --> 00:06:49,656
the thieves, and the art,

208
00:06:49,723 --> 00:06:50,723
are simply gone.

209
00:06:51,714 --> 00:06:53,628
Morning comes to the museum the

210
00:06:53,694 --> 00:06:54,867
way it always does.

211
00:06:54,934 --> 00:06:56,724
A staff member arrives for an

212
00:06:56,791 --> 00:06:59,260
ordinary shift and finds the unthinkable

213
00:06:59,326 --> 00:07:01,425
— two colleagues handcuffed in the

214
00:07:01,492 --> 00:07:03,652
basement, and upstairs, raw gaps on

215
00:07:03,719 --> 00:07:06,188
the walls where the world's masterpieces

216
00:07:06,255 --> 00:07:07,860
had hung the night before.

217
00:07:07,926 --> 00:07:09,284
The police are called.

218
00:07:09,351 --> 00:07:11,018
The frames are found empty,

219
00:07:11,084 --> 00:07:13,368
some with their canvases sliced clean

220
00:07:13,435 --> 00:07:15,534
away. In a single overnight shift,

221
00:07:15,600 --> 00:07:18,008
the Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum had

222
00:07:18,074 --> 00:07:19,988
become the scene of the largest

223
00:07:20,055 --> 00:07:21,907
art theft anyone had ever seen

224
00:07:21,973 --> 00:07:23,578
— and the clock that would

225
00:07:23,645 --> 00:07:25,620
run for decades, with no answer,

226
00:07:25,687 --> 00:07:26,921
had already started.

227
00:07:28,048 --> 00:07:30,270
Eighty-one minutes, start to finish.

228
00:07:30,337 --> 00:07:31,942
It is the last time anyone

229
00:07:32,008 --> 00:07:33,922
can say for certain where those

230
00:07:33,989 --> 00:07:35,223
thirteen works were.

231
00:07:36,285 --> 00:07:38,260
So what, exactly, walked out the

232
00:07:38,327 --> 00:07:39,327
door that night?

233
00:07:41,318 --> 00:07:42,985
Thirteen works in all — and

234
00:07:43,051 --> 00:07:44,718
not the tidy haul you might

235
00:07:44,785 --> 00:07:46,328
imagine. It is a strange,

236
00:07:46,395 --> 00:07:48,617
uneven list, and that strangeness is

237
00:07:48,683 --> 00:07:50,350
one of the great clues that

238
00:07:50,417 --> 00:07:52,145
has never quite been solved.

239
00:07:54,013 --> 00:07:55,309
The crown of it was a

240
00:07:55,376 --> 00:07:57,598
single painting by Johannes Vermeer,

241
00:07:57,665 --> 00:07:59,887
called "The Concert." Vermeer barely

242
00:07:59,954 --> 00:08:02,053
painted. Only about three dozen of

243
00:08:02,119 --> 00:08:03,848
his works are known to exist

244
00:08:03,914 --> 00:08:05,025
anywhere on earth.

245
00:08:05,092 --> 00:08:06,820
"The Concert" is one of them

246
00:08:06,887 --> 00:08:08,430
— and both the museum and

247
00:08:08,497 --> 00:08:10,102
the FBI have called it the

248
00:08:10,169 --> 00:08:12,699
most valuable unrecovered painting in the

249
00:08:12,766 --> 00:08:14,618
world. A quiet scene of people

250
00:08:14,685 --> 00:08:16,845
making music, now itself completely

251
00:08:16,912 --> 00:08:19,196
silent, its location unknown for over

252
00:08:19,262 --> 00:08:20,262
thirty years.

253
00:08:20,780 --> 00:08:22,817
To understand why losing that one

254
00:08:22,884 --> 00:08:24,982
painting matters so much, you have

255
00:08:25,049 --> 00:08:27,395
to understand how little Vermeer there

256
00:08:27,461 --> 00:08:28,461
is to lose.

257
00:08:28,528 --> 00:08:30,442
He worked slowly, died in debt,

258
00:08:30,508 --> 00:08:32,113
and left behind only a few

259
00:08:32,180 --> 00:08:34,340
dozen paintings in his entire life.

260
00:08:34,407 --> 00:08:36,444
Each one that survives is treated

261
00:08:36,511 --> 00:08:38,733
like a national treasure by whatever

262
00:08:38,800 --> 00:08:40,713
country is lucky enough to hold

263
00:08:40,780 --> 00:08:42,570
it. To have one simply vanish

264
00:08:42,637 --> 00:08:43,995
— cut out of the world

265
00:08:44,061 --> 00:08:45,975
for over thirty years, its fate

266
00:08:46,042 --> 00:08:47,770
unknown — is not like losing

267
00:08:47,837 --> 00:08:48,948
a valuable object.

268
00:08:49,015 --> 00:08:50,187
It is like a small,

269
00:08:50,254 --> 00:08:52,229
permanent hole in the history of

270
00:08:52,296 --> 00:08:53,296
human art.

271
00:08:53,817 --> 00:08:55,360
Then there was Rembrandt.

272
00:08:55,427 --> 00:08:56,970
They took his "A Lady and

273
00:08:57,037 --> 00:08:58,889
Gentleman in Black," and — the

274
00:08:58,955 --> 00:09:00,745
one that hurts most — "Christ

275
00:09:00,812 --> 00:09:02,232
in the Storm on the Sea

276
00:09:02,298 --> 00:09:03,965
of Galilee." It is a large,

277
00:09:04,032 --> 00:09:06,131
dramatic painting of a boat caught

278
00:09:06,197 --> 00:09:07,679
in a furious sea, and it

279
00:09:07,745 --> 00:09:10,029
carries a haunting distinction: it is

280
00:09:10,096 --> 00:09:12,318
the only seascape Rembrandt is known

281
00:09:12,385 --> 00:09:13,681
to have ever painted.

282
00:09:13,748 --> 00:09:14,748
The only one.

283
00:09:14,815 --> 00:09:16,234
And it was cut from its

284
00:09:16,301 --> 00:09:18,091
frame in the dark and carried

285
00:09:18,158 --> 00:09:19,158
into the night.

286
00:09:21,652 --> 00:09:23,257
But here is where the list

287
00:09:23,324 --> 00:09:25,731
gets strange. Alongside the Vermeer and

288
00:09:25,798 --> 00:09:28,082
the Rembrandts, the thieves took five

289
00:09:28,148 --> 00:09:29,568
works by Degas — small,

290
00:09:29,635 --> 00:09:32,227
delicate sketches and watercolors, not the

291
00:09:32,294 --> 00:09:34,763
artist's most famous or valuable pieces.

292
00:09:34,830 --> 00:09:35,941
They took a Manet.

293
00:09:36,008 --> 00:09:37,859
And then they took two objects

294
00:09:37,926 --> 00:09:40,148
that belong in an entirely different

295
00:09:40,215 --> 00:09:41,215
kind of crime.

296
00:09:41,824 --> 00:09:43,861
One was an ancient Chinese beaker

297
00:09:43,928 --> 00:09:45,533
— a bronze vessel called a

298
00:09:45,599 --> 00:09:47,698
Gu, some three thousand years old.

299
00:09:47,765 --> 00:09:49,493
The other was a small bronze

300
00:09:49,560 --> 00:09:51,350
eagle, a finial that had once

301
00:09:51,417 --> 00:09:54,009
topped a flagstaff belonging to Napoleon's

302
00:09:54,076 --> 00:09:56,360
imperial guard. Not paintings at all.

303
00:09:56,426 --> 00:09:58,834
Odd, specific, almost personal choices.

304
00:10:02,647 --> 00:10:04,931
And running underneath the whole list

305
00:10:04,998 --> 00:10:05,998
is a riddle.

306
00:10:06,064 --> 00:10:08,225
The thieves walked right past works

307
00:10:08,291 --> 00:10:10,452
that experts say were more valuable

308
00:10:10,519 --> 00:10:12,247
than some of what they took.

309
00:10:12,314 --> 00:10:14,536
They spent precious minutes prying a

310
00:10:14,603 --> 00:10:16,084
bronze eagle off a pole.

311
00:10:16,151 --> 00:10:18,064
People who study this case have

312
00:10:18,131 --> 00:10:20,168
argued for decades over what that

313
00:10:20,235 --> 00:10:22,642
means. Were they amateurs grabbing what

314
00:10:22,709 --> 00:10:25,116
they recognized? Were they working from

315
00:10:25,183 --> 00:10:26,417
someone else's list?

316
00:10:26,484 --> 00:10:28,212
Or did the strange haul mean

317
00:10:28,279 --> 00:10:30,501
something we still don't understand?

318
00:10:30,568 --> 00:10:32,235
That oddness is not a small

319
00:10:32,301 --> 00:10:33,598
detail — it is one of

320
00:10:33,664 --> 00:10:35,516
the few real clues the thieves

321
00:10:35,583 --> 00:10:37,928
left behind. Professional art thieves,

322
00:10:37,995 --> 00:10:39,724
the kind who steal to order,

323
00:10:39,790 --> 00:10:41,642
tend to be surgical: they take

324
00:10:41,709 --> 00:10:44,116
the most valuable, most portable pieces

325
00:10:44,183 --> 00:10:45,356
and leave the rest.

326
00:10:45,422 --> 00:10:47,706
These thieves did something closer to

327
00:10:47,773 --> 00:10:50,366
the opposite. They damaged masterpieces by

328
00:10:50,432 --> 00:10:51,482
cutting them out.

329
00:10:51,548 --> 00:10:53,709
They skipped works of immense value

330
00:10:53,775 --> 00:10:56,245
hanging nearby. They spent their limited

331
00:10:56,311 --> 00:10:58,657
minutes unscrewing a bronze eagle from

332
00:10:58,724 --> 00:11:01,193
a pole. Decades later, investigators and

333
00:11:01,259 --> 00:11:03,790
historians still cannot fully explain the

334
00:11:03,857 --> 00:11:05,524
logic — and the haul itself

335
00:11:05,590 --> 00:11:07,998
remains one of the most-studied riddles

336
00:11:08,064 --> 00:11:09,064
in the case.

337
00:11:09,462 --> 00:11:11,190
And then there is the number

338
00:11:11,257 --> 00:11:13,788
everyone repeats: half a billion dollars.

339
00:11:13,855 --> 00:11:15,583
Around five hundred million.

340
00:11:15,650 --> 00:11:17,316
It is a staggering figure —

341
00:11:17,383 --> 00:11:18,988
and you have to be careful

342
00:11:19,055 --> 00:11:20,055
with it.

343
00:11:21,136 --> 00:11:23,296
Because that number is an estimate,

344
00:11:23,363 --> 00:11:24,363
not a price.

345
00:11:24,430 --> 00:11:26,096
These works are some of the

346
00:11:26,163 --> 00:11:28,571
most recognizable stolen objects on the

347
00:11:28,637 --> 00:11:30,551
planet. You cannot walk into an

348
00:11:30,617 --> 00:11:33,025
auction house with a cut-out Rembrandt.

349
00:11:33,092 --> 00:11:34,758
The museum itself has said,

350
00:11:34,825 --> 00:11:36,553
bluntly, that it is the only

351
00:11:36,620 --> 00:11:37,978
buyer for these works.

352
00:11:38,045 --> 00:11:39,958
Which means their true value is

353
00:11:40,025 --> 00:11:42,556
almost philosophical — they are priceless

354
00:11:42,622 --> 00:11:44,783
precisely because they can never be

355
00:11:44,850 --> 00:11:45,850
sold.

356
00:11:45,916 --> 00:11:47,706
In the movies there is always

357
00:11:47,773 --> 00:11:50,119
a shadowy collector — some billionaire

358
00:11:50,185 --> 00:11:51,914
who buys a stolen Vermeer to

359
00:11:51,980 --> 00:11:53,462
gloat over it alone in a

360
00:11:53,529 --> 00:11:55,936
hidden vault. In reality, investigators

361
00:11:56,003 --> 00:11:57,669
say that figure is mostly a

362
00:11:57,736 --> 00:11:59,711
myth. There is no orderly market

363
00:11:59,778 --> 00:12:02,371
for the most recognizable stolen paintings

364
00:12:02,437 --> 00:12:04,227
on earth. They are too famous

365
00:12:04,294 --> 00:12:05,837
to hang, too hot to sell,

366
00:12:05,904 --> 00:12:07,571
and worth a fortune only on

367
00:12:07,637 --> 00:12:09,859
paper. Which leaves whoever ended up

368
00:12:09,926 --> 00:12:11,778
holding the Gardner art with a

369
00:12:11,845 --> 00:12:13,882
peculiar curse: sitting on half a

370
00:12:13,948 --> 00:12:16,356
billion dollars they can never actually

371
00:12:16,422 --> 00:12:17,422
spend.

372
00:12:17,735 --> 00:12:19,649
That single fact — unsellable —

373
00:12:19,715 --> 00:12:21,505
is the key to everything that

374
00:12:21,572 --> 00:12:23,733
comes next. Because it changes what

375
00:12:23,799 --> 00:12:25,528
kind of crime this even was.

376
00:12:28,666 --> 00:12:30,641
Most thefts are about turning an

377
00:12:30,708 --> 00:12:31,819
object into money.

378
00:12:31,886 --> 00:12:33,799
But thirteen of the most famous

379
00:12:33,866 --> 00:12:35,780
artworks in the world cannot be

380
00:12:35,846 --> 00:12:36,957
turned into money.

381
00:12:37,024 --> 00:12:38,814
So either the thieves did not

382
00:12:38,881 --> 00:12:40,609
understand that — or the art

383
00:12:40,676 --> 00:12:42,343
was never really the point.

384
00:12:42,409 --> 00:12:44,261
And every theory about who did

385
00:12:44,328 --> 00:12:46,056
this, and why, has to answer

386
00:12:46,123 --> 00:12:47,123
that question.

387
00:12:47,352 --> 00:12:48,895
A crime this big does not

388
00:12:48,962 --> 00:12:50,690
go quietly. The hunt for the

389
00:12:50,757 --> 00:12:52,547
Gardner art became one of the

390
00:12:52,614 --> 00:12:55,021
largest art-crime investigations in FBI

391
00:12:55,088 --> 00:12:57,187
history, and it has never formally

392
00:12:57,253 --> 00:12:58,253
closed.

393
00:12:59,630 --> 00:13:01,420
In the early years, the trail

394
00:13:01,487 --> 00:13:03,092
was hot and useless at the

395
00:13:03,158 --> 00:13:04,949
same time. Thousands of tips.

396
00:13:05,015 --> 00:13:07,299
Psychics. Con men claiming they could

397
00:13:07,366 --> 00:13:09,094
get the paintings back — for

398
00:13:09,161 --> 00:13:10,766
a price. The case drew the

399
00:13:10,832 --> 00:13:13,363
curious, the criminal, and the desperate,

400
00:13:13,430 --> 00:13:14,973
and almost none of it led

401
00:13:15,040 --> 00:13:16,040
anywhere.

402
00:13:17,805 --> 00:13:19,163
For a case with so few

403
00:13:19,230 --> 00:13:21,761
hard facts, it generated an extraordinary

404
00:13:21,827 --> 00:13:23,062
amount of attention.

405
00:13:23,128 --> 00:13:24,733
It became, over the years,

406
00:13:24,800 --> 00:13:26,899
the most famous unsolved art theft

407
00:13:26,965 --> 00:13:28,570
in the world — the subject

408
00:13:28,637 --> 00:13:31,168
of books, documentaries, podcasts, and an

409
00:13:31,235 --> 00:13:33,519
endless stream of armchair detectives

410
00:13:33,585 --> 00:13:35,437
convinced they had cracked it.

411
00:13:35,504 --> 00:13:37,603
The FBI fielded thousands of leads

412
00:13:37,669 --> 00:13:39,953
from across the country and overseas.

413
00:13:40,020 --> 00:13:41,440
And that is part of the

414
00:13:41,506 --> 00:13:43,482
tragedy of a mystery this large:

415
00:13:43,548 --> 00:13:45,215
the more famous it becomes,

416
00:13:45,282 --> 00:13:47,010
the more noise it generates,

417
00:13:47,077 --> 00:13:48,496
and the harder it is to

418
00:13:48,563 --> 00:13:50,291
tell a real whisper from the

419
00:13:50,358 --> 00:13:52,210
roar of people who simply want

420
00:13:52,277 --> 00:13:53,758
to be part of the story.

421
00:13:53,953 --> 00:13:56,113
One painful thread ran back through

422
00:13:56,180 --> 00:13:57,847
the museum's own door — the

423
00:13:57,913 --> 00:13:59,580
guard who buzzed the men in

424
00:13:59,647 --> 00:14:02,054
that night. Investigators looked at him

425
00:14:02,121 --> 00:14:04,713
closely; that is simply what investigators

426
00:14:04,780 --> 00:14:06,385
do. But it is important to

427
00:14:06,452 --> 00:14:08,427
be precise: he was never charged

428
00:14:08,494 --> 00:14:10,407
with anything, and he was found

429
00:14:10,474 --> 00:14:12,264
tied up in that basement with

430
00:14:12,331 --> 00:14:14,430
the rest. Being scrutinized is not

431
00:14:14,496 --> 00:14:16,039
the same as being guilty,

432
00:14:16,106 --> 00:14:18,205
and decades of suspicion are their

433
00:14:18,272 --> 00:14:19,876
own kind of sentence for a

434
00:14:19,943 --> 00:14:21,672
man who was never accused in

435
00:14:21,738 --> 00:14:22,738
court.

436
00:14:22,805 --> 00:14:24,842
And that caution — the difference

437
00:14:24,909 --> 00:14:26,699
between a suspect and a thief

438
00:14:26,765 --> 00:14:28,247
— is the thread you have

439
00:14:28,313 --> 00:14:30,351
to hold through this entire case.

440
00:14:30,417 --> 00:14:32,516
Because over thirty years, a great

441
00:14:32,583 --> 00:14:34,126
many names have surfaced.

442
00:14:34,193 --> 00:14:35,983
Local criminals. Mob figures.

443
00:14:36,049 --> 00:14:37,963
Men who claimed they knew where

444
00:14:38,030 --> 00:14:39,511
the art was, or knew who

445
00:14:39,578 --> 00:14:41,430
took it, or wanted the reward.

446
00:14:41,728 --> 00:14:43,580
But here is the discipline the

447
00:14:43,647 --> 00:14:45,498
facts demand. Not one of those

448
00:14:45,565 --> 00:14:47,602
people has ever been charged with

449
00:14:47,669 --> 00:14:49,397
the theft. The FBI has never

450
00:14:49,464 --> 00:14:51,130
publicly named the thieves.

451
00:14:51,197 --> 00:14:53,296
And the men sometimes described in

452
00:14:53,363 --> 00:14:55,647
books and documentaries as the likely

453
00:14:55,713 --> 00:14:57,997
robbers were named by journalists and

454
00:14:58,064 --> 00:14:59,792
authors — not by the Bureau.

455
00:14:59,859 --> 00:15:01,526
Some of the people who have

456
00:15:01,592 --> 00:15:03,382
been linked to this case over

457
00:15:03,449 --> 00:15:05,054
the years are still alive.

458
00:15:05,121 --> 00:15:06,417
And a theory is not a

459
00:15:06,484 --> 00:15:08,150
verdict. So we are going to

460
00:15:08,217 --> 00:15:10,254
tell you what law enforcement has

461
00:15:10,321 --> 00:15:12,296
actually said — and stop exactly

462
00:15:12,363 --> 00:15:13,906
where the evidence stops.

463
00:15:14,114 --> 00:15:16,274
What law enforcement has said came,

464
00:15:16,341 --> 00:15:17,699
most clearly, in 2013.

465
00:15:17,766 --> 00:15:20,112
On the twenty-third anniversary of the

466
00:15:20,178 --> 00:15:22,030
heist, the FBI made a striking

467
00:15:22,097 --> 00:15:24,257
announcement. It said it believed —

468
00:15:24,324 --> 00:15:25,929
with what it called a high

469
00:15:25,995 --> 00:15:27,847
degree of confidence — that it

470
00:15:27,914 --> 00:15:30,074
had finally identified the thieves.

471
00:15:31,825 --> 00:15:33,492
But it would not name them.

472
00:15:33,558 --> 00:15:35,410
The FBI described them only as

473
00:15:35,477 --> 00:15:37,946
members of a criminal organization based

474
00:15:38,013 --> 00:15:40,111
in the Mid-Atlantic states and New

475
00:15:40,178 --> 00:15:42,339
England. And it said something that

476
00:15:42,405 --> 00:15:44,627
reframed the entire case: the people

477
00:15:44,694 --> 00:15:47,225
it believed responsible were likely dead.

478
00:15:47,292 --> 00:15:49,205
Two years later, the Bureau put

479
00:15:49,272 --> 00:15:50,877
it even more plainly — the

480
00:15:50,944 --> 00:15:52,610
two men who carried out the

481
00:15:52,677 --> 00:15:54,529
heist, it said, were deceased.

482
00:15:54,784 --> 00:15:56,265
It was a strange kind of

483
00:15:56,332 --> 00:15:58,184
announcement — a triumph and a

484
00:15:58,251 --> 00:15:59,979
dead end in the same breath.

485
00:16:00,046 --> 00:16:01,465
The FBI was, in effect,

486
00:16:01,532 --> 00:16:03,446
saying: we have solved the part

487
00:16:03,512 --> 00:16:05,117
of the case that no longer

488
00:16:05,184 --> 00:16:07,098
matters, and lost the part that

489
00:16:07,164 --> 00:16:08,893
does. We believe we know the

490
00:16:08,959 --> 00:16:10,811
hands that took the paintings.

491
00:16:10,878 --> 00:16:12,421
We just can no longer ask

492
00:16:12,488 --> 00:16:14,216
them anything — and they can

493
00:16:14,283 --> 00:16:16,011
no longer give the art back.

494
00:16:18,997 --> 00:16:20,540
Sit with what that means.

495
00:16:20,607 --> 00:16:22,150
The FBI is telling you it

496
00:16:22,217 --> 00:16:24,130
thinks it knows who walked into

497
00:16:24,197 --> 00:16:25,925
that museum — and that those

498
00:16:25,992 --> 00:16:28,029
men are now beyond any courtroom.

499
00:16:28,096 --> 00:16:30,195
The question was never really "can

500
00:16:30,261 --> 00:16:32,113
we catch them." For years now,

501
00:16:32,180 --> 00:16:34,093
the question has been narrower,

502
00:16:34,160 --> 00:16:35,950
and sadder: where did the art

503
00:16:36,017 --> 00:16:37,313
go after they had it?

504
00:16:38,565 --> 00:16:40,972
To shake something loose, investigators

505
00:16:41,039 --> 00:16:42,582
went public in a way they

506
00:16:42,649 --> 00:16:44,748
rarely do. They launched an appeal

507
00:16:44,814 --> 00:16:46,296
to the whole country — a

508
00:16:46,363 --> 00:16:48,955
dedicated website, images of every missing

509
00:16:49,022 --> 00:16:51,182
work, even billboards in the region

510
00:16:51,249 --> 00:16:53,039
where the trail had last been

511
00:16:53,106 --> 00:16:54,896
warm. The message was simple,

512
00:16:54,963 --> 00:16:57,123
and a little desperate: someone out

513
00:16:57,190 --> 00:16:58,671
there has seen this art.

514
00:16:58,738 --> 00:16:59,738
On a wall.

515
00:16:59,805 --> 00:17:00,805
In an attic.

516
00:17:00,871 --> 00:17:01,871
In a back room.

517
00:17:01,938 --> 00:17:03,605
We need that person to pick

518
00:17:03,671 --> 00:17:04,671
up the phone.

519
00:17:05,054 --> 00:17:06,782
On that, the FBI offered its

520
00:17:06,849 --> 00:17:09,195
best answer. It said the investigation

521
00:17:09,261 --> 00:17:11,113
traced the stolen works out of

522
00:17:11,180 --> 00:17:13,217
Boston — to Connecticut, and then

523
00:17:13,284 --> 00:17:14,827
to the Philadelphia area.

524
00:17:14,894 --> 00:17:16,560
And it said that, roughly a

525
00:17:16,627 --> 00:17:18,849
decade before the 2013 announcement,

526
00:17:18,916 --> 00:17:20,397
some of the art had been

527
00:17:20,464 --> 00:17:22,501
offered for sale in Philadelphia.

528
00:17:22,568 --> 00:17:24,543
After that, the trail goes cold.

529
00:17:24,610 --> 00:17:26,338
The FBI has said, in effect:

530
00:17:26,405 --> 00:17:27,886
we followed it this far,

531
00:17:27,953 --> 00:17:29,187
and then we lost it.

532
00:17:29,254 --> 00:17:30,674
We do not know where it

533
00:17:30,740 --> 00:17:31,740
is now.

534
00:17:32,564 --> 00:17:34,292
Think about how a trail like

535
00:17:34,359 --> 00:17:35,359
that goes cold.

536
00:17:35,426 --> 00:17:37,278
Stolen art that cannot be sold

537
00:17:37,344 --> 00:17:39,258
openly tends to drift through a

538
00:17:39,324 --> 00:17:41,423
hidden world — used as collateral,

539
00:17:41,490 --> 00:17:42,786
as a favor, as a chip

540
00:17:42,853 --> 00:17:44,766
in some other deal, passed from

541
00:17:44,833 --> 00:17:46,438
hand to hand by people who

542
00:17:46,505 --> 00:17:48,480
have every reason never to talk.

543
00:17:48,547 --> 00:17:50,213
Each time it changes hands,

544
00:17:50,280 --> 00:17:52,132
the knowledge of where it sits

545
00:17:52,199 --> 00:17:54,174
gets thinner, and the people who

546
00:17:54,241 --> 00:17:55,845
hold the secret get fewer.

547
00:17:55,912 --> 00:17:57,517
By the time the FBI traced

548
00:17:57,584 --> 00:17:59,683
it to Philadelphia, it may already

549
00:17:59,749 --> 00:18:00,799
have moved again.

550
00:18:00,865 --> 00:18:02,532
A painting can be hidden in

551
00:18:02,599 --> 00:18:03,599
a single room.

552
00:18:03,665 --> 00:18:05,455
The truth about where it went

553
00:18:05,522 --> 00:18:07,312
can be hidden inside a single

554
00:18:07,379 --> 00:18:08,984
person — and people do not

555
00:18:09,050 --> 00:18:10,050
last forever.

556
00:18:10,117 --> 00:18:11,784
And there is one more twist

557
00:18:11,850 --> 00:18:13,764
that changes the whole shape of

558
00:18:13,831 --> 00:18:16,053
the hunt. The statute of limitations

559
00:18:16,120 --> 00:18:18,095
on the theft itself has expired.

560
00:18:18,162 --> 00:18:19,828
In plain terms: even if you

561
00:18:19,895 --> 00:18:21,808
walked into an FBI office today

562
00:18:21,875 --> 00:18:24,097
and confessed to robbing the Gardner

563
00:18:24,164 --> 00:18:25,954
Museum in 1990, you could not

564
00:18:26,021 --> 00:18:27,749
be prosecuted for the theft.

565
00:18:27,816 --> 00:18:29,483
The clock ran out long ago.

566
00:18:29,549 --> 00:18:31,216
At first that sounds like a

567
00:18:31,283 --> 00:18:33,073
failure. But it is actually a

568
00:18:33,139 --> 00:18:35,176
tool. Because it means the people

569
00:18:35,243 --> 00:18:36,910
who matter most now are not

570
00:18:36,976 --> 00:18:38,828
the thieves — they are whoever

571
00:18:38,895 --> 00:18:40,562
is quietly holding the art.

572
00:18:40,628 --> 00:18:42,604
And to those people, the message

573
00:18:42,670 --> 00:18:45,263
from prosecutors has been remarkably open:

574
00:18:45,329 --> 00:18:47,120
we are far more interested in

575
00:18:47,186 --> 00:18:49,162
getting these works back than in

576
00:18:49,228 --> 00:18:50,586
putting you in a cell.

577
00:18:50,653 --> 00:18:52,813
They have signaled a willingness to

578
00:18:52,880 --> 00:18:54,670
consider immunity. There is a

579
00:18:54,737 --> 00:18:57,206
ten-million-dollar reward. You would not

580
00:18:57,273 --> 00:18:59,186
even have to hand the paintings

581
00:18:59,253 --> 00:19:00,253
over in person.

582
00:19:00,320 --> 00:19:01,986
And the museum has tried to

583
00:19:02,053 --> 00:19:04,090
make saying something as easy and

584
00:19:04,157 --> 00:19:05,823
as safe as it possibly can.

585
00:19:05,890 --> 00:19:08,112
The ten-million-dollar reward is for

586
00:19:08,179 --> 00:19:10,524
information that leads to the recovery

587
00:19:10,591 --> 00:19:12,381
of all thirteen works in good

588
00:19:12,448 --> 00:19:14,423
condition. You would not have to

589
00:19:14,490 --> 00:19:16,218
march into a police station.

590
00:19:16,285 --> 00:19:18,260
You could work through a lawyer,

591
00:19:18,327 --> 00:19:20,920
protect your identity, keep your distance.

592
00:19:20,986 --> 00:19:22,900
The whole offer is built around

593
00:19:22,966 --> 00:19:24,818
one almost gentle idea: we are

594
00:19:24,885 --> 00:19:26,428
not hunting you — we just

595
00:19:26,495 --> 00:19:27,495
want them back.

596
00:19:27,562 --> 00:19:29,352
Bring the art home, and there

597
00:19:29,418 --> 00:19:31,085
is a fortune, and a measure

598
00:19:31,152 --> 00:19:32,324
of safety, waiting.

599
00:19:33,424 --> 00:19:35,338
The whole machinery of the law,

600
00:19:35,404 --> 00:19:37,380
in other words, has been quietly

601
00:19:37,446 --> 00:19:39,298
rebuilt around a single goal —

602
00:19:39,365 --> 00:19:40,970
not justice for the theft,

603
00:19:41,036 --> 00:19:43,012
which is now impossible, but the

604
00:19:43,078 --> 00:19:45,424
return of thirteen objects that cannot

605
00:19:45,491 --> 00:19:46,491
be replaced.

606
00:19:47,652 --> 00:19:49,195
So if the FBI believes it

607
00:19:49,262 --> 00:19:50,929
knows who did it, and there

608
00:19:50,995 --> 00:19:52,971
is a fortune waiting for whoever

609
00:19:53,037 --> 00:19:54,704
returns the art, and no one

610
00:19:54,771 --> 00:19:56,437
even has to fear prison for

611
00:19:56,504 --> 00:19:57,924
the theft — why are the

612
00:19:57,990 --> 00:19:59,163
frames still empty?

613
00:20:01,230 --> 00:20:02,897
That is the real mystery of

614
00:20:02,963 --> 00:20:04,013
the Gardner case.

615
00:20:04,079 --> 00:20:05,684
Not so much whodunit — but

616
00:20:05,751 --> 00:20:07,850
why, after all this, nothing comes

617
00:20:07,916 --> 00:20:08,916
back.

618
00:20:10,489 --> 00:20:12,156
There are really only a few

619
00:20:12,222 --> 00:20:14,321
possibilities, and none of them is

620
00:20:14,388 --> 00:20:15,388
comfortable.

621
00:20:15,707 --> 00:20:17,312
The first is the simplest,

622
00:20:17,379 --> 00:20:18,379
and the worst.

623
00:20:18,445 --> 00:20:19,742
The art may be gone —

624
00:20:19,808 --> 00:20:22,030
destroyed. Stolen goods this hot are

625
00:20:22,097 --> 00:20:24,072
a danger to everyone who touches

626
00:20:24,139 --> 00:20:26,053
them. Someone, at some point in

627
00:20:26,119 --> 00:20:28,342
three decades, may have decided that

628
00:20:28,408 --> 00:20:30,075
the safest thing to do with

629
00:20:30,142 --> 00:20:31,747
a painting no one can sell

630
00:20:31,813 --> 00:20:33,480
is to make it disappear for

631
00:20:33,547 --> 00:20:34,905
good. If that is true,

632
00:20:34,971 --> 00:20:36,947
the empty frames are not waiting

633
00:20:37,013 --> 00:20:39,174
for anything. They are gravestones.

634
00:20:41,592 --> 00:20:43,197
The second is that the art

635
00:20:43,264 --> 00:20:44,992
is still out there — sitting

636
00:20:45,059 --> 00:20:46,787
in an attic, a storage unit,

637
00:20:46,854 --> 00:20:48,582
a basement — held by someone

638
00:20:48,649 --> 00:20:50,501
who inherited it, or is afraid

639
00:20:50,567 --> 00:20:52,111
of it, or simply does not

640
00:20:52,177 --> 00:20:53,412
know what they have.

641
00:20:53,478 --> 00:20:55,701
Masterpieces have resurfaced before,

642
00:20:55,767 --> 00:20:57,866
decades later, in stranger places.

643
00:20:57,933 --> 00:21:00,340
The reward exists precisely because the

644
00:21:00,407 --> 00:21:02,320
FBI and the museum believe this

645
00:21:02,387 --> 00:21:03,387
is possible.

646
00:21:05,619 --> 00:21:07,224
And the third is the quiet

647
00:21:07,291 --> 00:21:09,266
ache underneath the whole case —

648
00:21:09,333 --> 00:21:11,123
that the few people who truly

649
00:21:11,189 --> 00:21:12,979
knew where it went have taken

650
00:21:13,046 --> 00:21:14,713
the answer to their graves.

651
00:21:14,779 --> 00:21:16,261
If the thieves are dead,

652
00:21:16,328 --> 00:21:17,994
and the middlemen are dead,

653
00:21:18,061 --> 00:21:19,728
then the location of half a

654
00:21:19,794 --> 00:21:21,646
billion dollars in art may now

655
00:21:21,713 --> 00:21:23,318
exist in no living mind at

656
00:21:23,384 --> 00:21:24,384
all.

657
00:21:24,451 --> 00:21:26,365
The leading theory, the one law

658
00:21:26,431 --> 00:21:29,024
enforcement's own statements point toward,

659
00:21:29,091 --> 00:21:30,634
is that this was the work

660
00:21:30,700 --> 00:21:32,923
of organized crime — local criminals

661
00:21:32,989 --> 00:21:34,594
who saw an easy target and

662
00:21:34,661 --> 00:21:36,328
a famous prize, and who may

663
00:21:36,394 --> 00:21:38,246
have grabbed the art with only

664
00:21:38,313 --> 00:21:39,671
a vague idea of how to

665
00:21:39,738 --> 00:21:41,219
ever turn it into money.

666
00:21:41,286 --> 00:21:43,199
That would explain the strange,

667
00:21:43,266 --> 00:21:45,550
amateurish haul. It would explain why

668
00:21:45,617 --> 00:21:47,468
nothing was ever quietly sold.

669
00:21:47,535 --> 00:21:49,572
And it would explain the silence:

670
00:21:49,639 --> 00:21:51,429
in that world, the people who

671
00:21:51,496 --> 00:21:53,594
know things are exactly the people

672
00:21:53,661 --> 00:21:55,204
who never, ever say them.

673
00:21:55,271 --> 00:21:56,814
If that is what happened,

674
00:21:56,881 --> 00:21:58,300
then the art was less a

675
00:21:58,367 --> 00:22:00,034
treasure than a curse — too

676
00:22:00,100 --> 00:22:01,705
hot to sell, too famous to

677
00:22:01,772 --> 00:22:03,809
show, too valuable to throw away.

678
00:22:05,561 --> 00:22:07,228
And woven through all of it

679
00:22:07,294 --> 00:22:09,517
are the smaller mysteries that never

680
00:22:09,583 --> 00:22:11,929
resolved. Like the strange detail from

681
00:22:11,996 --> 00:22:14,403
inside the museum that night: according

682
00:22:14,470 --> 00:22:16,630
to the museum's own security chief,

683
00:22:16,697 --> 00:22:18,796
the motion sensors recorded no one

684
00:22:18,862 --> 00:22:20,652
but a guard ever entering one

685
00:22:20,719 --> 00:22:22,386
of the rooms a painting was

686
00:22:22,452 --> 00:22:24,428
taken from. A work vanished from

687
00:22:24,494 --> 00:22:26,161
a space the system says the

688
00:22:26,228 --> 00:22:27,833
thieves never walked into.

689
00:22:27,899 --> 00:22:30,307
A small, maddening puzzle, decades old,

690
00:22:30,373 --> 00:22:31,670
with no clean answer.

691
00:22:33,211 --> 00:22:34,754
And there is a human cost

692
00:22:34,821 --> 00:22:36,426
to an open wound like this

693
00:22:36,492 --> 00:22:38,283
that is easy to forget behind

694
00:22:38,349 --> 00:22:40,386
the half-billion-dollar headline.

695
00:22:40,453 --> 00:22:42,181
A museum that has spent more

696
00:22:42,248 --> 00:22:44,100
than three decades as the site

697
00:22:44,167 --> 00:22:45,216
of a famous loss.

698
00:22:45,283 --> 00:22:47,196
A city that quietly adopted the

699
00:22:47,263 --> 00:22:48,436
mystery as its own.

700
00:22:48,502 --> 00:22:50,786
Investigators who gave years of their

701
00:22:50,853 --> 00:22:52,581
careers to a case that never

702
00:22:52,648 --> 00:22:54,068
let them reach the end.

703
00:22:54,134 --> 00:22:56,110
And, somewhere, two men who were

704
00:22:56,176 --> 00:22:58,213
young guards on an ordinary shift

705
00:22:58,280 --> 00:23:00,255
and have carried that night with

706
00:23:00,322 --> 00:23:01,322
them ever since.

707
00:23:01,389 --> 00:23:03,055
The empty frames are a loss

708
00:23:03,122 --> 00:23:04,542
for the history of art.

709
00:23:04,609 --> 00:23:06,399
They are also a loss measured

710
00:23:06,465 --> 00:23:07,576
in ordinary lives.

711
00:23:07,643 --> 00:23:09,495
This is what makes the Gardner

712
00:23:09,562 --> 00:23:11,784
heist different from the crimes that

713
00:23:11,851 --> 00:23:12,900
get tidy endings.

714
00:23:12,967 --> 00:23:14,633
There is no trial to watch.

715
00:23:14,700 --> 00:23:16,305
No verdict to argue about.

716
00:23:16,371 --> 00:23:18,347
No moment where a detective lays

717
00:23:18,413 --> 00:23:19,957
it all out and the pieces

718
00:23:20,023 --> 00:23:21,813
click. There is only a slowly

719
00:23:21,880 --> 00:23:23,732
cooling trail, a list of names

720
00:23:23,799 --> 00:23:25,774
that never became charges, and a

721
00:23:25,841 --> 00:23:27,939
building that decided to leave the

722
00:23:28,006 --> 00:23:29,006
wound open.

723
00:23:29,073 --> 00:23:31,295
You would think a ten-million-dollar

724
00:23:31,362 --> 00:23:33,275
reward would be enough to break

725
00:23:33,342 --> 00:23:34,515
almost any silence.

726
00:23:34,581 --> 00:23:36,371
The fact that it hasn't tells

727
00:23:36,438 --> 00:23:38,537
you something cold about where the

728
00:23:38,604 --> 00:23:39,715
art may have gone.

729
00:23:39,781 --> 00:23:41,818
Either the people who could claim

730
00:23:41,885 --> 00:23:43,367
it are dead, or they are

731
00:23:43,433 --> 00:23:45,779
more frightened of something than they

732
00:23:45,846 --> 00:23:48,006
are tempted by ten million dollars,

733
00:23:48,073 --> 00:23:49,986
or there is simply nothing left

734
00:23:50,053 --> 00:23:51,053
to bring back.

735
00:23:51,120 --> 00:23:53,218
A reward that large, unclaimed for

736
00:23:53,285 --> 00:23:55,137
this long, stops being just an

737
00:23:55,204 --> 00:23:57,241
offer. It becomes evidence — that

738
00:23:57,307 --> 00:23:59,591
whatever happened to the Gardner art,

739
00:23:59,658 --> 00:24:01,510
it is buried deeper than money

740
00:24:01,576 --> 00:24:02,576
can reach.

741
00:24:02,643 --> 00:24:04,248
Because that was a choice.

742
00:24:04,315 --> 00:24:06,537
The museum could have quietly filled

743
00:24:06,604 --> 00:24:08,517
those spaces — moved a painting

744
00:24:08,584 --> 00:24:10,621
over, hung something new, let the

745
00:24:10,688 --> 00:24:12,971
walls heal. Instead, the empty frames

746
00:24:13,038 --> 00:24:15,199
stay exactly where the stolen works

747
00:24:15,265 --> 00:24:17,611
hung. In part because Isabella Stewart

748
00:24:17,678 --> 00:24:19,838
Gardner's own wishes asked that her

749
00:24:19,905 --> 00:24:22,004
collection be kept as she arranged

750
00:24:22,070 --> 00:24:23,799
it. And in part as something

751
00:24:23,865 --> 00:24:26,149
more deliberate: a refusal to pretend

752
00:24:26,216 --> 00:24:28,253
it didn't happen, and a standing,

753
00:24:28,320 --> 00:24:30,048
public hope that one day the

754
00:24:30,115 --> 00:24:31,843
frames will be filled again.

755
00:24:32,817 --> 00:24:34,854
Every visitor who stands in front

756
00:24:34,921 --> 00:24:36,464
of one of those frames is

757
00:24:36,531 --> 00:24:38,321
looking at the same thing the

758
00:24:38,387 --> 00:24:39,622
thieves left behind.

759
00:24:39,689 --> 00:24:40,689
Not a painting.

760
00:24:40,755 --> 00:24:41,755
A question.

761
00:24:41,822 --> 00:24:43,427
More than thirty years on,

762
00:24:43,494 --> 00:24:45,777
the Gardner heist has outlived almost

763
00:24:45,844 --> 00:24:47,387
everyone connected to it.

764
00:24:47,454 --> 00:24:48,627
The guards grew up.

765
00:24:48,694 --> 00:24:50,607
The lead investigators retired.

766
00:24:50,674 --> 00:24:52,402
The men the FBI believes did

767
00:24:52,469 --> 00:24:54,136
it are, by its own account,

768
00:24:54,202 --> 00:24:56,301
gone. And still, the most valuable

769
00:24:56,368 --> 00:24:57,973
stolen art on earth is out

770
00:24:58,039 --> 00:24:59,829
there somewhere — or it isn't

771
00:24:59,896 --> 00:25:01,748
— and the frames keep waiting.

772
00:25:04,013 --> 00:25:05,494
It is tempting to want a

773
00:25:05,561 --> 00:25:07,166
villain, a name, a face to

774
00:25:07,233 --> 00:25:09,208
blame. But the honest version of

775
00:25:09,275 --> 00:25:11,435
this story is harder, and stranger.

776
00:25:11,502 --> 00:25:12,860
It is a crime that has

777
00:25:12,927 --> 00:25:14,717
slipped past the reach of the

778
00:25:14,783 --> 00:25:16,388
law, past the lives of the

779
00:25:16,455 --> 00:25:18,492
people who committed it, and into

780
00:25:18,559 --> 00:25:20,411
something closer to a legend —

781
00:25:20,477 --> 00:25:22,576
except that the loss is completely

782
00:25:22,643 --> 00:25:24,248
real, and it is hanging on

783
00:25:24,314 --> 00:25:25,981
a wall in Boston right now.

784
00:25:28,504 --> 00:25:29,985
And maybe that is why it

785
00:25:30,052 --> 00:25:31,534
holds us. We are used to

786
00:25:31,600 --> 00:25:32,773
stories that close.

787
00:25:32,840 --> 00:25:34,321
This one simply refuses.

788
00:25:34,388 --> 00:25:36,795
Somewhere, perhaps, a Vermeer is rolled

789
00:25:36,862 --> 00:25:38,220
in a tube in the dark.

790
00:25:38,287 --> 00:25:39,583
Or perhaps it is ash.

791
00:25:39,650 --> 00:25:40,650
We do not know.

792
00:25:40,716 --> 00:25:42,692
And the not-knowing is the whole

793
00:25:42,758 --> 00:25:45,166
point — a half-billion-dollar question,

794
00:25:45,232 --> 00:25:47,208
with empty gold frames where the

795
00:25:47,274 --> 00:25:48,324
answer should be.

796
00:25:51,649 --> 00:25:54,242
There is something almost unbearable about

797
00:25:54,308 --> 00:25:56,037
a loss that just stays open.

798
00:25:56,103 --> 00:25:57,461
A murder gets a trial.

799
00:25:57,528 --> 00:25:58,763
A war gets a treaty.

800
00:25:58,829 --> 00:26:00,496
Even most thefts end with a

801
00:26:00,563 --> 00:26:02,106
recovery or an arrest or,

802
00:26:02,172 --> 00:26:03,654
at least, a closed file.

803
00:26:03,721 --> 00:26:05,696
The Gardner heist gives you none

804
00:26:05,763 --> 00:26:07,182
of that. It asks you to

805
00:26:07,249 --> 00:26:08,854
live with not knowing — to

806
00:26:08,921 --> 00:26:11,205
accept that one ordinary March night,

807
00:26:11,271 --> 00:26:13,555
thirteen pieces of the world's memory

808
00:26:13,622 --> 00:26:15,289
walked out a door, and that

809
00:26:15,355 --> 00:26:16,960
they may be sitting in the

810
00:26:17,027 --> 00:26:19,002
dark somewhere right now, or may

811
00:26:19,069 --> 00:26:20,921
be gone forever, and that both

812
00:26:20,987 --> 00:26:23,271
of those things feel equally possible

813
00:26:23,338 --> 00:26:24,449
and equally wrong.

814
00:26:27,053 --> 00:26:29,028
If those frames ever fill again,

815
00:26:29,095 --> 00:26:30,885
it will likely be because one

816
00:26:30,952 --> 00:26:32,989
ordinary person — someone who saw

817
00:26:33,055 --> 00:26:35,093
something, in an attic, a storage

818
00:26:35,159 --> 00:26:36,702
unit, a quiet back room —

819
00:26:36,769 --> 00:26:38,683
finally decided to make a call.

820
00:26:38,749 --> 00:26:40,478
After all this time, that is

821
00:26:40,544 --> 00:26:41,655
still how it ends.

822
00:26:41,722 --> 00:26:43,018
Not with a detective.

823
00:26:43,085 --> 00:26:44,085
With a witness.

824
00:26:48,944 --> 00:26:50,672
So while those frames wait —

825
00:26:50,739 --> 00:26:52,714
do one small thing that actually

826
00:26:52,781 --> 00:26:54,509
helps. If a mystery this big

827
00:26:54,576 --> 00:26:56,551
should never be allowed to fade,

828
00:26:56,618 --> 00:26:58,100
tap like, and subscribe.

829
00:26:58,166 --> 00:27:00,203
It keeps stories like this alive,

830
00:27:00,270 --> 00:27:01,998
and it costs you nothing but

831
00:27:02,065 --> 00:27:03,065
a second.

832
00:27:04,658 --> 00:27:06,633
Because the next call might come

833
00:27:06,700 --> 00:27:08,675
from someone who watched a video

834
00:27:08,742 --> 00:27:09,915
just like this one.

835
00:27:09,981 --> 00:27:11,525
Stay with us — next time,

836
00:27:11,591 --> 00:27:13,443
we open another case the world

837
00:27:13,510 --> 00:27:15,300
was never supposed to forget.
